{"title":"An Open Letter To The Go Team About Try","description":"“Once a language gets complex enough, programming in it is more like carving out a subset from an infinite sea of features, most of which we’ll never learn. Once a language feels infinite, the costs of adding further features to it are no longer apparent\u0026rdquo;. - Mark Miller The new try proposal is an addition to the language that introduces a second mechanic to handle errors. It is being introduced in response to data gathered from the 2018 Go Survey and a review of proposals that were submitted during the Go 2 proposal process.","html":"\u0026lt;div style=\u0026#34;display:flex; border: 1px solid #d4d4d4; width:100%\u0026#34;\u0026gt;\u0026lt;div class=\u0026#34;embed-content\u0026#34; style=\u0026#34;flex; padding: 1rem;\u0026#34;\u0026gt;\u0026lt;a href=\u0026#34;https://www.ardanlabs.com/blog/2019/07/an-open-letter-to-the-go-team-about-try.html\u0026#34;\u0026gt;\u0026lt;div class=\u0026#34;title\u0026#34; style=\u0026#34;font-weight: 800; margin-bottom: 1rem; font-size:120%\u0026#34;\u0026gt;An Open Letter To The Go Team About Try\u0026lt;/div\u0026gt;\u0026lt;/a\u0026gt;\u0026lt;div class=\u0026#34;embed-description\u0026#34; style=\u0026#34;margin-bottom:1rem; font-size:80%\u0026#34;\u0026gt;“Once a language gets complex enough, programming in it is more like carving out a subset from an infinite sea of features, most of which we’ll never learn. Once a language feels infinite, the costs of adding further features to it are no longer apparent\u0026amp;amp;rdquo;. - Mark Miller The new try proposal is an addition to the language that introduces a second mechanic to handle errors. It is being introduced in response to data gathered from the 2018 Go Survey and a review of proposals that were submitted during the Go 2 proposal process.\u0026lt;/div\u0026gt;\u0026lt;div class=\u0026#34;embed-meta\u0026#34; style=\u0026#34;font-size:60%\u0026#34;\u0026gt;\u0026lt;div style=\u0026#34;float:left;